docs.abstract: Sheriff Christopher R. Swanson of Genesee County walked with demonstrators protesting police brutality and the death of George Floyd.
docs.snippet: Sheriff Christopher R. Swanson of Genesee County walked with demonstrators protesting police brutality and the death of George Floyd.
docs.lead_paragraph: Sheriff Christopher R. Swanson of Genesee County in Michigan stood before a crowd of protesters on Saturday. They were outraged over the death last week of George Floyd in Minneapolis, police brutality and systemic racism.

headline.main: Michigan Sheriff Took Off His Helmet and Marched With Protesters

docs.abstract: People with the most to gain from his agenda have also been the most disappointed by politics.
docs.snippet: People with the most to gain from his agenda have also been the most disappointed by politics.
docs.lead_paragraph: The story about Bernie Sanders is that he can’t win black voters. That first emerged when he lost the Democratic presidential nomination in 2016 and was reinforced by Joe Biden’s decisive sweep of Southern primaries.

headline.main: Why Sanders Isn’t Winning Over Black Voters

docs.abstract: The dash cam video shows a police officer beating Allan Adam, chief of the Athabasca Chipewyan First Nation in northern Alberta.
docs.snippet: The dash cam video shows a police officer beating Allan Adam, chief of the Athabasca Chipewyan First Nation in northern Alberta.
docs.lead_paragraph: TORONTO — The police dash cam video shows the Indigenous chief being held by one police officer and tackled to the ground by another, punched in the head and put in a chokehold.

headline.main: Video of Arrest of Indigenous Leader Shocks Canada
headline.print_headline: ‘Shocking’: Police Video of Arrest of Indigenous Leader Rattles Canada

docs.abstract: June is Pride Month, but high rents and little-to-no income mean establishments including the Stonewall Inn are “facing an uncertain future.”
docs.snippet: June is Pride Month, but high rents and little-to-no income mean establishments including the Stonewall Inn are “facing an uncertain future.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Protesters have returned to the Stonewall Inn again and again in recent weeks to demand an end to police brutality, raising their fists, taking a knee and holding moments of silence on the same ground where a riot in 1969 helped spark the modern gay rights movement.

headline.main: Can Gay Bars, an Anchor of N.Y.C. Nightlife, Survive the Pandemic?

docs.lead_paragraph: In the nation’s capital, blocks from the White House, scores of sharply dressed Americans mingled Thursday night over cocktails and collard greens, a glittering coming-out party for the College Board’s first advanced placement course in African American studies.

docs.abstract: The W.N.B.A.’s Atlanta Dream backed a candidate for the Senate running directly against a co-owner of the team; the N.F.L.’s Atlanta Falcons promoted voter participation in general.
docs.snippet: The W.N.B.A.’s Atlanta Dream backed a candidate for the Senate running directly against a co-owner of the team; the N.F.L.’s Atlanta Falcons promoted voter participation in general.
docs.lead_paragraph: Georgia’s runoff election on Tuesday will have dramatic consequences, deciding whether Republicans or Democrats control the Senate. In an environment of heightened civic engagement for athletes, two of Atlanta’s pro teams have been rallying voters there in starkly different ways.

headline.main: In Georgia, Pro Teams Dive Into Senate Races With Different Playbooks
headline.print_headline: Atlanta Teams Differ in Strategies to Get Out Vote
